[2] Guinea: resurgence
Date: Thu 4 Mar 2021 14:07 EST
Source: The Conversation [in French, translated, abridged, edited]
https://theconversation.com/la-guinee-face-a-la-resurgence-de-lepidemie-debola-155876


On 14 Feb [2021], Guinea's health authorities declared the country "in an epidemic situation" after the confirmation of 7 cases of infection with the Ebola virus, including 3 deaths. The whole of West Africa finds itself in a delicate situation, with a real risk of a resurgence of the Ebola epidemic 5 years after a 1st deadly wave that left more than 11 000 dead.

Between March 2014 and December 2015, a national epidemic due to the Ebola virus was declared in Guinea (a resurgence was recorded in 2016 in the prefecture of Nzerekore, but it was quickly contained). The disease then spread very quickly to neighboring countries, notably Liberia and Sierra Leone, with 10 066 and 12 666 cases, respectively. Faced with the rapid spread of the virus, movement restrictions had been imposed, borders closed, and air links suspended.

This year [2021], the virus appeared in the sub-prefecture of Gouecke, a locality with high mobility towards the regional capital, Nzerekore. Being an agroforestry production area, the movement of people and products is a major risk factor for the spread of the disease. Already, a contact of patient zero has been identified in Conakry: he would have previously traveled a distance of about a thousand kilometers (about 620 mi). This means that the risk of the virus spreading to other prefectures or other countries is real. It is this fear that motivates the closure of borders and the slowdown in trade and tourism flows.

At the end of the 2014 epidemic, Guinea had carried out an analysis of the risks of epidemics and disasters that populations could face. This analysis highlighted the significant risk of a resurgence of certain diseases, in particular that caused by the Ebola virus. In total, 9 priority zoonotic diseases (rabies, anthrax, Ebola, dengue, brucellosis, avian influenza, yellow fever, Lassa fever, Rift Valley fever) have been identified and placed under surveillance within the framework of the One Health integrated approach. It is therefore not surprising that the Ebola virus is now resurfacing in Guinea.

At the end of the epidemic in 2016, the Guinean government set up the National Health Security Agency (ANSS), the national institution in charge of managing epidemics, emergencies and health disasters. The agency has been provided with 38 epidemic treatment centers for the management of cases of diseases with epidemic potential, in accordance with the administrative subdivision of the country. For the management of epidemic cases in the communities, 17 improved health centers were built.

The national capacity in terms of laboratories and logistics has been improved. The country now has a network of 5 certified laboratories in Conakry, capable of detecting the main diseases with epidemic potential. Two local laboratories have been set up in the prefectures of Gueckedou and Kindia. The means of transport (motorcycles and cars) have been reinforced to ensure better mobility of the intervention teams.

For emergency interventions in the response to epidemics, the management of the agency has been decentralized. In addition to the national management, epidemic alert and response teams have been set up at the level of regions (regional epidemic alert and response teams [ERARE]) and prefectures (prefectural epidemic alert and response teams [EPARE]). The capacity of the vaccination teams has been strengthened for the implementation of screening activities.

The experiences of the response to the 2014 epidemic and the participation of Guinean teams in the response to Ebola in the DRC have strengthened national capacities in terms of epidemic management.

The principle of responsiveness in interventions is one of the lessons learned from the management of past epidemics. Epidemics spread quickly, with lots of rumors supporting them. The ANSS has already acquired the vaccines to prevent the spread of the virus. The epidemic treatment centers are on alert. With the experience resulting from the management of COVID-19, a videoconferencing system has been set up to coordinate interventions in the different prefectures. Measures have also been implemented to mobilize and involve community nationals in crisis management alongside the ANSS.

The media are also called upon to counter rumors about the existence of the disease, about preventive behavior or even those linked to the involvement of political authorities. To do this, information on the epidemic is regularly shared with them through the social networks of the agency to which they are members.

The 2014 epidemic was marked by the persistence of community reluctance. These take the form of the refusal to identify contact persons; hiding and/or caring for the sick in the community; transporting and cleaning the bodies of people who have died from Ebola; exposure for funeral orations of suspected or proven bodies; unsafe community burials; refusal to allow Red Cross agents to disinfect places believed to be infected, etc.; and verbal and physical violence against actors who do not share these beliefs. This reluctance, whatever its form and nature, is due to ignorance of the disease, received ideas and intervention errors by actors.

It has often happened that it was not the messages that were the problem, but the people who conveyed them. People often tend not to trust people outside their own community. Likewise, the hasty recruitment of inexperienced young people into communities is not without consequences. It was observed during the 2014 epidemic that the protocols for appointing members of community teams (village/neighborhood watch committees) were not respected. The new recruits lacked legitimacy, motivation and availability. The actions they carried out were not based on any result indicator. The gender dimension has often been ignored in the constitution of community teams.

It has been observed that contact persons leave their homes as soon as (a) the monitoring agents are not trustworthy and are considered as strangers in the locality; (b) the disease considered fatal is associated with their locality; (c) the contact is gossiped or stigmatized. Often, people fleeing their locality will already have developed 3 types of fears that will encourage them to leave: fear of suffering the same fate as the deceased, fear of going to the Ebola Treatment Center (CTE) considered as a dying [place], and fear of stigma. Taxi drivers are the 1st accomplices of people who secretly leave their communities.

The Ebola death management system disrupts funeral practices. As a result, cases of community deaths are not reported to allow dignified and secure care (DHS) by specialists. The populations accused the agents in charge of the DHS of not being reactive enough. This poses the problem of the conservation of bodies. Also, families reserve the "sacred" duty to wash the body for the 1st time before community rituals.

Finally, the massive deployment of agents and vehicles for the response in the same place at the same time provokes a feeling of invasion among the populations. This spirit of competition between the partners in the response is detrimental to the spirit of teamwork and sharing.

--
